	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1" facs="EHRI-BF-19380906_01.jpg"/>
			<p>[...] Indeed, it is characteristic of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3078198/cechy.html">Bohemia</placeName>, where <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-778" type="subject">nationality</term>
				<pb n="2" facs="EHRI-BF-19380906_02.jpg"/> is a matter of language rather than of blood, that speech rather than origin is the
				distinguishing characteristic of friend or foe. Such resentment of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term> as exists in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3078198/cechy.html">Bohemia</placeName> thus centers largely on the German-speaking <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term> – particularly those who have come to
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3078198/cechy.html">Bohemia</placeName> since the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080" type="subject">war</term>.</p>
			<p>Among the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8505031/czechoslovakia.html">Czechs</placeName> themselves, there is comparatively
				little <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-329" type="subject">anti-semitism</term>. Only the small
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8505031/czechoslovakia.html">Czech</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-964" type="subject">fascist groups</term> and certain sections of the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1017" type="subject">nationalist</term>-<term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-973" type="subject">conservative</term> element are <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-329" type="subject">anti-semitic</term>. This applies particularly to the
				younger element in the <orgName ref="#ehri_dr_new_national_unitiy_party">New National Unity Party</orgName> , which is being organized
				as a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-948" type="subject">government</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-958" type="subject">party</term>. All these elements together, however,
				make up only a small <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1062" type="subject">minority</term> of the
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8505031/czechoslovakia.html">Czech</placeName> population. The mass of the people appear
				simply to have very little interest in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-329" type="subject"
					>anti-semitism</term>.</p>
			<p>The present talk of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-337" type="subject">anti-semitic measures</term> and
				the general <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-829" type="subject">anxiety</term> of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jewish population</term> is due principally to the
				pressure which is being brought to bear on the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8505031/czechoslovakia.html">Czech</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-948" type="subject">Government</term> by <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2950159/berlin.html">Berlin</placeName> in the direction of an <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-339" type="subject">anti-Jewish policy</term>. There is no doubt of the
				existence of this pressure. [...]</p>
			<p>Very little has happened in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName> thus far to justify the
				panicky atmosphere which has prevailed in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jewish
					circles</term> here since the Munich agreement. The vast majority of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3078198/cechy.html">Bohemia</placeName> and <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3070359/moravia.html">Moravia</placeName> have remained up to the present quite unmolested both in
				their private <pb n="3" facs="EHRI-BF-19380906_03.jpg"/> lives and their <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-918" type="subject">economic</term> activities. [...]</p>
			<p>In <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3057568/slovak-republic.html">Slovakia</placeName>, other conditions prevail. Here the
				percentage of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term>, in the first place, is
				higher than in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3078198/cechy.html">Bohemia</placeName>. The <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3057568/slovak-republic.html">Slovak</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term> are not only prominent in the cities
				but, in contrast to the situation prevailing in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3078198/cechy.html">Bohemia</placeName>, are
				scattered in large numbers throughout the countryside and play a conspicuous part in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-918" type="subject">economic life</term> of the <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3057568/slovak-republic.html">Slovak</placeName> village. They are the object of widespread
				resentment on the part of the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3057568/slovak-republic.html">Slovak</placeName> population.
				Many of them are of the poorer <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-774" type="subject">orthodox</term> type.
				Their <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">dress</term>, their manners and their habits
				are conspicuous and – to many <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3057568/slovak-republic.html">Slovaks</placeName> – offensive.
				They are prominent in the villages as money-lenders, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-899" type="subject"
					>lawyers</term>, saloon-keepers, druggists, merchants, etc. In the larger cities they form a wealthy class which makes up a good
				part of the <q>intelligentsia</q> and controls a very large proportion of the capital of the country.</p>
			<p>Many of the educated <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term> are <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/719819/hungary.html">Hungarian</placeName>-speaking and have always looked to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3054643/budapest.html">Budapest</placeName> for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-672" type="subject">cultural</term> inspiration. <pb n="4"
					facs="EHRI-BF-19380906_04.jpg"/> A smaller but by no means insignificant number have had a <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html">German</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-672" type="subject">cultural</term> orientation. This doubtless explains
				to a large extent the feeling prevalent in many <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3057568/slovak-republic.html"
					>Slovak</placeName> circles to the effect that the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896"
					type="subject">Jews</term> have always sided with the oppressors of the <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3057568/slovak-republic.html">Slovaks</placeName>, against the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">native population</term>. [...]</p>
			<pb n="5" facs="EHRI-BF-19380906_05.jpg"/>
			<p>As will have been seen from the above discussion, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-351" type="subject"
					>Jewish question</term> in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8505031/czechoslovakia.html">Czechoslovakia</placeName>
				presents a highly confused picture. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term>
				themselves fall into many different categories, varying from the highly <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-672" type="subject">cultured</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-798" type="subject">intellectuals</term> of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName> to the pious and primitive <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-774" type="subject">orthodox</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term> of the <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3057568/slovak-republic.html">Slovak</placeName> and Ruthenian villages. They are divided among
				various <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-672" type="subject">cultural</term> tendencies: Yiddish,
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html">German</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/719819/hungary.html">Hungarian</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/798544/republic-of-poland.html">Polish</placeName> and <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/8505031/czechoslovakia.html">Czechoslovak</placeName>. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-815" type="subject">attitude</term> of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373" type="subject">Aryan</term> population toward them varies again,
				between city and country, between the various classes and professions, between the different provinces. In these circumstances, it is
				scarcely to be expected that any clear-cut <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-947" type="subject"
					>policy</term> or <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-815" type="subject">attitude</term> on the part of
				the responsible authorities will emerge. It seems evident that if <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8505031/czechoslovakia.html"
					>Czechoslovakia</placeName> existed in a vacuum the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896"
					type="subject">Jews</term>, despite their considerable number, would not present any <ref
					target="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/vocabularies/ehri_terms/search?q=judenfrage">problem</ref> which could not be solved with
				relatively humane and painless <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-337" type="subject">methods</term>. The
				country does not contain in itself the basis for a really serious and widespread <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-352" type="subject">anti-semitic movement</term>.</p>
